Definition: to succinctly retell the main points of a story or argument
Explanations: This breakdown disagrees, to some degree, with both LN and BDAG. LN gives only one sense and groups both Romans 13:9 and Ephesians 1:10 together under this one sense. However, this seems unworkable since the idea of summarizing the main point of various laws is not the same thing as unifying all things in heaven and earth. BDAG lists two senses, but strangely lists both verses under the idea “to sum up or recapitulate (of literary or rhetorical summation)” and then gives the alternative that Romans 13:9 means “to sum up (of mathematical total).” This is odd as Paul is dealing with laws, not numbers.

Definition: to combine, to be together as a unit
Explanations: LN’s explanation seems a bit muddled here. Ephesians 4:16 and Colossians 2:2 are listed under the sense “to bring together into a unit”, though they are often translated “hold together”. There does actually seem to be a difference here. By introducing the idea of bringing into a unit, this implies that they formerly were not united which does not seem to be present in these verses about the body and Body. “Being combined” or “being a unit” seems the clearer meaning. It does not seem necessary to introduce the concept of “hold together” since holding seems to introduce another idea of a force that is keeping something from coming apart. The simplest and most precise definition would seem to be “to combine or be together as a unit.”
